{"title_page": "Chaudhry Muhammad Sarwar Khan", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name = Chaudhry Muhammad Sarwar Khan<br><small>\u0686\u0648\u06c1\u062f\u0631\u06cc \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0633\u0631\u0648\u0631 \u062e\u0627\u0646</small> \t\n|image = Ch_Muhammad_Sarwar_Khan.jpg\t  \n|caption = Ch. Muhammad Sarwar Khan (Left) meeting President [[Suharto]] (Right) of [[Indonesia]] \n}}\n\n'''Chaudhry Muhammad Sarwar Khan''' ({{lang-ur|'''\u0686\u0648\u06c1\u062f\u0631\u06cc \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0633\u0631\u0648\u0631 \u062e\u0627\u0646'''}}; 1919-2003); was a renowned and the longest serving [[Member of Parliament|Parliamentarian]] in the history of [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://narowal.dc.lhc.gov.pk/?page_id=1335 |title=DISTRICT & SESSIONS COURT, NAROWAL |publisher=District Courts Narowal  |date= |accessdate=3 December 2012}}</ref> He served in [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]] and [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] from 1951 to 1999. The first direct elections held in Pakistan after independence were for the Provincial Assembly of the Punjab between 10\u201320 March 1951.  He was elected as a Member of Legislative Assembly in 1951. He was again elected in the 1962 and 1964 Provincial Assembly elections in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pap.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/19/595 |title=Punjab Assembly of Pakistan |publisher=Na.gov.pk |date= |accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe was elected as Member of the National Assembly of Pakistan in 1985, 1988, 1990, 1993 and 1997 General Elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ecp.gov.pk/GE/MNAs7297.aspx |title=Election Commission of Pakistan |publisher=Ecp.gov.pk |accessdate=23 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317230833/http://www.ecp.gov.pk/GE/MNAs7297.aspx |archivedate=17 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Despite being a stalwart of Pakistan Muslim League, Mr Sarwar accompanied Prime Minister [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] for [[Simla Agreement]] in India in 1972 to ease the tensions between the two countries following the Indo-Pak war of 1971. On 24 December 1981, a Federal Council ([[Majlis-e-Shoora]]) was constituted by then President [[General Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq]], Its members were nominated by the President. Khan served in the Federal Council from 1982\u20131984.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}} In 1997 he was appointed as chairman [[Parliamentary Special Committee on Kashmir]] by then Prime Minister of Pakistan [[Muhammad Nawaz Sharif]]. He led Kashmir Committee composed of 26 MNA's from May 1997 to October 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.na.gov.pk/en/content.php?id=82 |title=National Assembly of Pakistan |publisher=Na.gov.pk |date= |accessdate=2 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the landslide victory of Pakistan Muslim League ([[PML-N]]) in the 1997 parliamentary elections, Khan was nominated as the presidential candidate by the party but ultimately [[Nawaz Sharif]] appointed Rafique Tarar as the president of Pakistan.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nAfter the 1999 coup d'\u00e9tat staged by General [[Pervez Musharraf]], Prime Minister [[Nawaz Sharif]] was exiled to [[Saudi Arabia]]. Following the exile, Khan was nominated as the party president, however due to old age and deteriorating health he refused the party presidency and it was passed on to Makhdoom [[Javed Hashmi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siasat.pk/forum/showthread.php?103040-Nawaz-sharif-wanted-Chaudhry-sarwar-khan-to-be-the-president-of-the-party-instead-of-javed-hashmi-after-the-1999-coup-shah-m |title=Geo news pakistan |publisher=siasat.pk |date= |accessdate=2 December 2012}}</ref> Khan was referred as ''\"Baba-e-Muslim League\"'' by [[Nawaz Sharif]] due to his lifelong services in politics of Pakistan.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nDuring [[Kargil War]], as the Chairman of National Assembly Kashmir Committee, Khan addressed the [[United Nations Commission on Human Rights]] (UNCHR) in Geneva and asked the world powers to give Kashmiris the right of self-determination according to UN resolutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.pk/books?id=ExtuAAAAMAAJ&q=chaudhry+muhammad+sarwar+mna&dq=chaudhry+muhammad+sarwar+mna&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwikpf-Q8PnoAhUQxcQBHdyGDPMQ6AEIJDAA |title=Foreign Affairs Pakistan, Volume 25 |publisher=Policy planning division, Ministry of Foreign-Affairs, Government of Pakistan |date= |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Family background==\n[[File:Chaudhry Sarwar United Nations visit.jpg|thumb|Chaudhry Sarwar (Right) representing Pakistan at [[United Nations]] [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]].]]\n\nCh. Muhammad Sarwar Khan was born in a well known Sulehria [[Rajput]] ([[Rajput]] Clan) family of Rupochak, District [[Narowal]] cum [[Sialkot]] . He was a respected politician from Rupochak, [[Narowal]]. His father Khan Bahadur Qasim and uncle Kazim Khan both served in the [[British Indian army]]. Khan Bahadur Qasim won the 1937 election from the state of [[Kashmir and Jammu]] and his younger brother Kazim khan held a top bureaucratic post in [[British Raj]] after retirement. Ch.Muhammad Sarwar Khan's grandfather Hashim Khan also served in the British Indian Army during [[World War I]] in \"[[58th Vaughan's Rifles (Frontier Force)]]\" regiment and was awarded the Highest \"Medal of Gallantry\" during his service with [[Herbert Kitchener|Lord Kitchener]] in the [[Third Anglo-Afghan War]]. Hashim khan's father Sazawar Khan died fighting against the British during 1857 [[Indian Mutiny]], his grandfather Abdul Nabi Khan was a [[Nawab]] in the Mughal court (No Hazari) and was under an obligation to provide 9000 troops to the [[Mughal Empire]].<ref>Page 151, ''Fateh&nbsp;'' by Haroon-ur-Rasheed, Aligarh books Pakistan 2007</ref>\n\nKhan's younger brother Ch. Ghulam Ahmed Khan was a seasoned right-wing politician of [[Pakistan Muslim League]], he was elected Member [[Provincial Assembly of Punjab]] (MPA) for five consecutive terms dating 1985 to 1999, prior to that he served as Chairman Union Council Rupochak from 1961 to 1964 and then from 1979 to 1987. Ch. Ghulam Ahmed was elected as Chairman Standing Committee on Local Government & Rural Development in 1997 and was further appointed as Parliamentary Secretary for Revenue in 1997 by the then [[Prime Minister of Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.pap.gov.pk/uploads/previous_members/1997-2001/dist17.htm|date= |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.pap.gov.pk/members/profile/en/20/984|date= |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nCh. Muhammad Sarwar's son Barrister Mansoor Sarwar Khan is the first elected President of Central Punjab and Member Core-Committee and National Council Pakistan of [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]], Central Punjab is composed of Lahore and Gujranwala divisions having ten districts altogether.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dawn.com/2013/03/14/ptis-mansoor-basra-win-party-poll/|title=Dawn Newspaper |publisher=dawn.com |date= |accessdate=17 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insaf.pk/about-us/office-of-the-secretary-general/item/1793199-notification-core-committee/|title=Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf|publisher=insaf.pk|date=|accessdate=23 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324174753/http://www.insaf.pk/about-us/office-of-the-secretary-general/item/1793199-notification-core-committee/|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Chaudhry Muhammad Sarwar}}\n[[Category:Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf politicians]]\n[[Category:Narowal District]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name = Chaudhry Muhammad Sarwar Khan<br><small>\u0686\u0648\u06c1\u062f\u0631\u06cc \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0633\u0631\u0648\u0631 \u062e\u0627\u0646</small> \t\n|image = Ch_Muhammad_Sarwar_Khan.jpg\t  \n|caption = Ch. Muhammad Sarwar Khan (Left) meeting President [[Suharto]] (Right) of [[Indonesia]] \n}}\n\n'''Chaudhry Muhammad Sarwar Khan''' ({{lang-ur|'''\u0686\u0648\u06c1\u062f\u0631\u06cc \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0633\u0631\u0648\u0631 \u062e\u0627\u0646'''}}; 1919-2003); was a renowned and the longest serving [[Member of Parliament|Parliamentarian]] in the history of [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://narowal.dc.lhc.gov.pk/?page_id=1335 |title=DISTRICT & SESSIONS COURT, NAROWAL |publisher=District Courts Narowal  |date= |accessdate=3 December 2012}}</ref> He served in [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]] and [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] from 1951 to 1999. The first direct elections held in Pakistan after independence were for the Provincial Assembly of the Punjab between 10\u201320 March 1951.  He was elected as a Member of Legislative Assembly in 1951. He was again elected in the 1962 and 1964 Provincial Assembly elections in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pap.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/19/595 |title=Punjab Assembly of Pakistan |publisher=Na.gov.pk |date= |accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe was elected as Member of the National Assembly of Pakistan in 1985, 1988, 1990, 1993 and 1997 General Elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ecp.gov.pk/GE/MNAs7297.aspx |title=Election Commission of Pakistan |publisher=Ecp.gov.pk |accessdate=23 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317230833/http://www.ecp.gov.pk/GE/MNAs7297.aspx |archivedate=17 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Despite being a stalwart of Pakistan Muslim League, Mr Sarwar accompanied Prime Minister [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] for [[Simla Agreement]] in India in 1972 to ease the tensions between the two countries following the Indo-Pak war of 1971. On 24 December 1981, a Federal Council ([[Majlis-e-Shoora]]) was constituted by then President [[General Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq]], Its members were nominated by the President. Khan served in the Federal Council from 1982\u20131984.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}} In 1997 he was appointed as chairman [[Parliamentary Special Committee on Kashmir]] by then Prime Minister of Pakistan [[Muhammad Nawaz Sharif]]. He led Kashmir Committee composed of 26 MNA's from May 1997 to October 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.na.gov.pk/en/content.php?id=82 |title=National Assembly of Pakistan |publisher=Na.gov.pk |date= |accessdate=2 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the landslide victory of Pakistan Muslim League ([[PML-N]]) in the 1997 parliamentary elections, Khan was nominated as the presidential candidate by the party but ultimately [[Nawaz Sharif]] appointed Rafique Tarar as the president of Pakistan.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nAfter the 1999 coup d'\u00e9tat staged by General [[Pervez Musharraf]], Prime Minister [[Nawaz Sharif]] was exiled to [[Saudi Arabia]]. Following the exile, Khan was nominated as the party president, however due to old age and deteriorating health he refused the party presidency and it was passed on to Makhdoom [[Javed Hashmi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siasat.pk/forum/showthread.php?103040-Nawaz-sharif-wanted-Chaudhry-sarwar-khan-to-be-the-president-of-the-party-instead-of-javed-hashmi-after-the-1999-coup-shah-m |title=Geo news pakistan |publisher=siasat.pk |date= |accessdate=2 December 2012}}</ref> Khan was referred as ''\"Baba-e-Muslim League\"'' by [[Nawaz Sharif]] due to his lifelong services in politics of Pakistan.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nDuring [[Kargil War]], as the Chairman of National Assembly Kashmir Committee, Khan addressed the [[United Nations Commission on Human Rights]] (UNCHR) in Geneva and asked the world powers to give Kashmiris the right of self-determination according to UN resolutions.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\n==Family background==\n[[File:Chaudhry Sarwar United Nations visit.jpg|thumb|Chaudhry Sarwar (Right) representing Pakistan at [[United Nations]] [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]].]]\n\nCh. Muhammad Sarwar Khan was born in a well known Sulehria [[Rajput]] ([[Rajput]] Clan) family of Rupochak, District [[Narowal]] cum [[Sialkot]] . He was a respected politician from Rupochak, [[Narowal]]. His father Khan Bahadur Qasim and uncle Kazim Khan both served in the [[British Indian army]]. Khan Bahadur Qasim won the 1937 election from the state of [[Kashmir and Jammu]] and his younger brother Kazim khan held a top bureaucratic post in [[British Raj]] after retirement. Ch.Muhammad Sarwar Khan's grandfather Hashim Khan also served in the British Indian Army during [[World War I]] in \"[[58th Vaughan's Rifles (Frontier Force)]]\" regiment and was awarded the Highest \"Medal of Gallantry\" during his service with [[Herbert Kitchener|Lord Kitchener]] in the [[Third Anglo-Afghan War]]. Hashim khan's father Sazawar Khan died fighting against the British during 1857 [[Indian Mutiny]], his grandfather Abdul Nabi Khan was a [[Nawab]] in the Mughal court (No Hazari) and was under an obligation to provide 9000 troops to the [[Mughal Empire]].<ref>Page 151, ''Fateh&nbsp;'' by Haroon-ur-Rasheed, Aligarh books Pakistan 2007</ref>\n\nKhan's younger brother Ch. Ghulam Ahmed Khan was a seasoned right-wing politician of [[Pakistan Muslim League]], he was elected Member [[Provincial Assembly of Punjab]] (MPA) for five consecutive terms dating 1985 to 1999, prior to that he served as Chairman Union Council Rupochak from 1961 to 1964 and then from 1979 to 1987. Ch. Ghulam Ahmed was elected as Chairman Standing Committee on Local Government & Rural Development in 1997 and was further appointed as Parliamentary Secretary for Revenue in 1997 by the then[[Prime Minister of Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.pap.gov.pk/uploads/previous_members/1997-2001/dist17.htm|date= |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.pap.gov.pk/members/profile/en/20/984|date= |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nCh. Muhammad Sarwar's son Barrister Mansoor Sarwar Khan is the first elected President of Central Punjab and Member Core-Committee and National Council Pakistan of [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]], Central Punjab is composed of Lahore and Gujranwala divisions having ten districts altogether.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dawn.com/2013/03/14/ptis-mansoor-basra-win-party-poll/|title=Dawn Newspaper |publisher=dawn.com |date= |accessdate=17 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insaf.pk/about-us/office-of-the-secretary-general/item/1793199-notification-core-committee/|title=Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf|publisher=insaf.pk|date=|accessdate=23 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324174753/http://www.insaf.pk/about-us/office-of-the-secretary-general/item/1793199-notification-core-committee/|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Chaudhry Muhammad Sarwar}}\n[[Category:Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf politicians]]\n[[Category:Narowal District]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n", "name_user": "Mian.meraj", "label": "safe", "comment": "added a credible authentic and a verifiable reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chaudhry_Muhammad_Sarwar_Khan"}
{"title_page": "Luxgen S3", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile\n| image = Luxgen S3 China 2017-03-30.jpg\n| name = Luxgen S3\n| manufacturer = [[Luxgen]]\n| production = 2016&ndash;present\n| assembly = [[Miaoli City|Miaoli]], Taiwan\n| engine = 1.6 L [[Naturally aspirated engine]] [[Inline-four engine|I-4]]\n| transmission = [[Continuously variable transmission|CVT]] transmission\n| class = [[Subcompact car]]\n| body_style = 4-door [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]]\n| layout = [[FF layout|Front Engine, Front Wheel Drive]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2620|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|4551|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1783|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1527|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|1230-1250|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n| doors = 4\n| related = [[Luxgen U5]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Luxgen S3''' is a 5-seater subcompact sedan car produced by the [[Taiwan]]ese car company [[Luxgen]].\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:2016 Luxgen S3 (front).jpg|thumb|left|Luxgen S3 sedan front view]]\n[[File:2016 Luxgen S3 (rear).jpg|thumb|left|Luxgen S3 sedan rear view]]\n[[File:Luxgen S3 interior.jpg|thumb|left|The interior of Luxgen S3]]\nThe model is the first subcompact car of the brand and positioned under the [[Luxgen S5]] compact sedan. It was styled by the Taiwanese [[Hua-chuang Automobile Information Technical Center|HAITEC]] Design Center, and was previewed at the 2016 [[Taipei Auto Show]] as the Luxgen S3 EV+ concept. Luxgen S3 is the second sedan product of the Luxgen brand. It has a 1.6-liter [[Naturally aspirated engine|Naturally aspirated]] petrol engine giving {{Convert|116|hp|0|abbr=on}} at 6000 rpm and {{Convert|15.3|kgm|0|abbr=on}} at 4200 rpm. It is equipped with 3D X-View+ 3D vision assist system, Active Eagle View+360 degree camera system, and the Side View+ camera system. The initial launch includes 5 trim levels and with the starting price around $17,000.<ref>{{cite web|title= LUXGEN S3 Sedan taking orders|url=http://www.mobile01.com/topicdetail.php?f=444&t=4788550&p=1#60077997|publisher=mobile01|date=2016-05-03}}</ref> No hatchback version have been developed, but a subcompact hatchback crossover based on the sedan called the [[Luxgen U5]] has been introduced in 2017.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe MY2018 Luxgen S3 went on sale in January, 2018 in Taiwan. The new model features 6 air bags, ESC, TCS, HSA, and power adjust side mirrors in all trims. Other equipments include 12-inch display,  AR view+ system, and two-tone exterior.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tw.iscarmg.com/index.php/best-buy/roadtest/46924-luxgen-2018-01-09|title=isCar - 55.9\u842c\u8d77\u5920\u4e0d\u5920\u4fd7\u64f1\u5927\u7897\uff1fLuxgen S3\uff0c\u5927\u87a2\u5e55+6\u5b89\u5927\u6eff\u914d\uff01|last=\u5289\u5bb6\u5cb3Jason|work=isCar|access-date=2018-06-29|language=zh-tw}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==EV+==\nLuxgen also introduced a Luxgen S3 [[electric vehicle]] called the S3 EV+ co-developed by [[AC Propulsion]] just like the M7 EV+. originally launched before the petroleum-powered version S3 was on sale as the Luxgen S3 EV+ concept to preview the production petroleum-powered S3, the S3 EV+ is powered by E-Drive motors capable of up to {{Convert|150|kW|0|abbr=on}} with 33KWh batteries equivalent to {{Convert|204|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} maximum power output (Based on [[New European Driving Cycle]] tests). The S3 EV+ also supports AC/DC chargers and can be charged up to 80% in 40 minutes. <ref>{{cite web|title= LUXGEN S3 EV+ revealed|url=https://7car.tw/articles/read/41017|publisher=7car.tw|date=2017-02-22}}</ref>\n[[File:Luxgen S3 EV+.jpg|thumb|left|Luxgen S3 EV+ concept front view]]\n{{clear}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Luxgen}}\n\n[[Category:Luxgen vehicles|S3]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2016]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Subcompact cars]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n| image = Luxgen S3 China 2017-03-30.jpg\n| name = Luxgen S3\n| manufacturer = [[Luxgen]]\n| production = 2016&ndash;present\n| assembly = [[Miaoli City|Miaoli]], Taiwan\n| engine = 1.6 L [[Naturally aspirated engine]] [[Inline-four engine|I-4]]\n| transmission = [[Continuously variable transmission|CVT]] transmission\n| class = [[Subcompact car]]\n| body_style = 4-door [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]]\n| layout = [[FF layout|Front Engine, Front Wheel Drive]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2620|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|4551|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1783|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1527|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|1230-1250|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n| doors = 4\n| related = [[Luxgen U5]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Luxgen S3''' is a 5-seater subcompact sedan car produced by the [[Taiwan]]ese car company [[Luxgen]].\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:2016 Luxgen S3 (front).jpg|thumb|left|Luxgen S3 sedan front view]]\n[[File:2016 Luxgen S3 (rear).jpg|thumb|left|Luxgen S3 sedan rear view]]\n[[File:Luxgen S3 interior.jpg|thumb|left|The interior of Luxgen S3]]\nThe model is the first subcompact car of the brand and positioned under the [[Luxgen S5]] compact sedan. It was styled by the Taiwanese [[Hua-chuang Automobile Information Technical Center|HAITEC]] Design Center, and was previewed at the 2016 [[Taipei Auto Show]] as the Luxgen S3 EV+ concept. Luxgen S3 is the second sedan product of the Luxgen brand. It has a 1.6-liter [[Naturally aspirated engine|Naturally aspirated]] petrol engine giving {{Convert|116|hp|0|abbr=on}} at 6000 rpm and {{Convert|15.3|kgm|0|abbr=on}} at 4200 rpm. It is equipped with 3D X-View+ 3D vision assist system, Active Eagle View+360 degree camera system, and the Side View+ camera system. The initial launch includes 5 trim levels and with the starting price around $17,000.<ref>{{cite web|title= LUXGEN S3 Sedan taking orders|url=http://www.mobile01.com/topicdetail.php?f=444&t=4788550&p=1#60077997|publisher=mobile01|date=2016-05-03}}</ref> No hatchback version have been developed, but a subcompact hatchback crossover based on the sedan called the [[Luxgen U5]] has been introduced in 2017.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe MY2018 Luxgen S3 went on sale in January, 2018 in Taiwan. The new model features 6 air bags, ESC, TCS, HSA, and power adjust side mirrors in all trims. Other equipments include 12-inch display,  AR view+ system, and two-tone exterior.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tw.iscarmg.com/index.php/best-buy/roadtest/46924-luxgen-2018-01-09|title=isCar - 55.9\u842c\u8d77\u5920\u4e0d\u5920\u4fd7\u64f1\u5927\u7897\uff1fLuxgen S3\uff0c\u5927\u87a2\u5e55+6\u5b89\u5927\u6eff\u914d\uff01|last=\u5289\u5bb6\u5cb3Jason|work=isCar|access-date=2018-06-29|language=zh-tw}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==EV+==\nLuxgen also introduced a Luxgen S3 [[electric vehicle]] called the S3 EV+ co-developed by [[AC Propulsion]] just like the M7 EV+. originally launched before the petroleum-powered version S3 was on sale as the Luxgen S3 EV+ concept to preview the production petroleum-powered S3, the S3 EV+ is powered by E-Drive motors capable of up to {{Convert|150|kW|0|abbr=on}} with 33KWh batteries equivalent to {{Convert|204|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} maximum power output (Based on [[New European Driving Cycle]] tests). The S3 EV+ also supports AC/DC chargers and can be charged up to 80% in 40 minutes. <ref>{{cite web|title= LUXGEN S3 EV+ revealed|url=https://7car.tw/articles/read/41017|publisher=7car.tw|date=2017-02-22}}</ref>\n[[File:Luxgen S3 EV+.jpg|thumb|left|Luxgen S3 EV+ concept front view]]\n{{clear}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Luxgen}}\n\n[[Category:Luxgen vehicles|S3]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2016]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Subcompact cars]]\n[[Category:Cars of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n", "name_user": "TKOIII", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed redundant categories as per WP:Subcat. Parent category not needed when one of its subcategories is already present.", "url_page": "//en.