kson-pollock-and-lee-krasner-papers-8943 Jackson Pollock and Lee Krasner papers, circa 1905-1984], Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution\n*[http://www.pkf.org The Pollock-Krasner Foundation]\n*[http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-lee-krasner-12507 Oral history interview with Lee Krasner, 1964 Nov. 2-1968 Apr. 11]\n*[http://www.getty.edu/vow/ULANFullDisplay?find=Lee+Krasner&role=&nation=&prev_page=1&subjectid=500010144 Entry for Lee Krasner] on the [[Union List of Artist Names]]\n*{{Find a Grave|3812}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yFdE0bH9FRg 1978 Lee Krasner video interview] by [[Barbaralee Diamonstein-Spielvogel]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NrNQvA9K96M Women Artists and Postwar Abstraction | HOW TO SEE with MoMA curator Starr Figura]\n\n{{Feminist art movement in the United States}}\n{{Jackson Pollock}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krasner, Lee}}\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Painters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:Abstract expressionist artists]]\n[[Category:Abstract painters]]\n[[Category:American abstract artists]]\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:American printmakers]]\n[[Category:American women painters]]\n[[Category:American women printmakers]]\n[[Category:Modern painters]]\n[[Category:Jewish artists]]\n[[Category:Jewish painters]]\n[[Category:Art Students League of New York alumni]]\n[[Category:Cooper Union alumni]]\n[[Category:People from East Hampton (town), New York]]\n[[Category:Federal Art Project artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:Jackson Pollock]]\n[[Category:Burials at Green River Cemetery]]\n", "name_user": "GreytFolly", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRelationship with Jackson Pollock", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Krasner"}
{"title_page": "Luxgen M7", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2019}}{{Infobox automobile\n|image= Luxgen M7 Turbo EcoHyper facelift.jpg\n|name=Luxgen M7\n|aka=Luxgen M7 Turbo\n|manufacturer=[[Luxgen]]\n|production=2009&ndash;present\n|assembly= [[Miaoli City|Miaoli]], [[Taiwan]]\n|engine= 2.2 L [[Turbocharged]] [[Inline-four engine|I-4]]\n|transmission= 5 speed [[Manumatic]] transmission\n| wheelbase = {{Convert|2910|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|length= {{convert|4845|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|width= {{convert|1876|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|height= {{convert|1768|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|body_style=[[Minivan]]\n|weight= {{convert|1830|-|1875|kg|abbr=on}}\n|platform= L7 platform\n|layout=[[FF layout|Front Engine, Front Wheel Drive]]\n|related= [[Luxgen7 SUV]]\n}}\nThe '''Luxgen M7''', previously the '''Luxgen7 MPV''' is a 7-passenger [[Taiwan]]ese [[automobile]] produced by [[Luxgen]] beginning from 2009. \n\n==Overview==\nThe vehicle was developed under [[Yulon]]'s R&D center, [[Hua-chuang Automobile Information Technical Center|HAITEC]]. It was officially shown to the public on 19 August 2009, and hit showrooms on 9/19/2009. The car is powered by a 2.2 L [[Inline-4 engine|I-4]] MEFI turbocharged engine developed by tuned by [[Delphi (auto parts)|Delphi]]. The platform is derived from the [[Renault Espace]]. The turbocharger is supplied by [[Garrett AiResearch|Garrett]] and powers the engine up to {{convert|175|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5,200 rpm and {{convert|28|kgm|Nm lbft|abbr=on}} of torque from 2,500 to 4,000 rpm. The 5-speed [[Manumatic]] transmission is supplied by [[Aisin]]. Pricing starts at NT$798,000 up to NT$1,068,000. [[Antilock braking system|ABS]], [[Electronic brakeforce distribution|EBD]], [[Brake assist system|BAS]], and the Think+ Multi-purpose system(slightly different by trim level) are all standard equipment. The targeted competitor is the [[BYD Song Max]]. In 2014, the Luxgen7 MPV received a facelift and name change to Luxgen M7 to fit the new Luxgen naming theme.\n\nThe [[voice control]]led ''Luxgen Think+'' system (co-developed with [[HTC Corporation|HTC]]) combines the on-board [[Windows CE]] computer with the [[Electronic Stability Control]] system and it provides 3.5G mobile internet connection, [[GPS navigation device|GPS navigation]], along with travel, shop, and traffic information.<ref>[http://www.product-reviews.net/2009/08/25/taiwans-new-luxgen-7-mpv-features-htc-think-computer/ Taiwan\u2019s new LUXGEN 7 MPV features HTC THINK+ computer]</ref>\n\nA facelift was done in 2014 with a redesigned front bumper, dark head lamps with DRL, and a new set of LED tail lamps. The name was changed from Luxgen7 MPV to Luxgen M7 turbo Eco hyper, and the engine was also updated with a retuned 2.2- liter I4 turbo one with improved horsepower of 202PS and {{convert|30|kgm|Nm lbft|abbr=on}}  of torque from 2,400 to 4,000 rpm. The fuel efficiency was also improved to 13.57&nbsp;km/l(EPA) and 11.8&nbsp;km/l(EU).\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"120\">\nFile:Luxgen M7 001.jpg|Post-facelift Luxgen M7 front view (Taiwan)\nFile:Luxgen M7 002.jpg |Post-facelift Luxgen M7 rear view (Taiwan)\nFile:Luxgen7 2.2 MPV front view.jpg|Prefacelift Luxgen7 2.2 MPV front view (Vietnam)\nFile:Luxgen7 2.2 MPV rear view.jpg|Prefacelift Luxgen7 2.2 MPV rear view (Vietnam)\n\n\n</gallery>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==EV+==\nLuxgen also introduced the world's first electric MPV, Luxgen7 MPV [[electric vehicle]] co-developed by [[AC Propulsion]]. The top speed is {{convert|145|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}} and the electric range is {{convert|350|km|0|abbr=}} at {{convert|40|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.luxgen-motor.com.tw/cars/EV/ |title=Luxgen EV (Chinese) |access-date=2009-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090922215709/http://www.luxgen-motor.com.tw/cars/EV/ |archive-date=2009-09-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nWhile most of the exterior was based on the regular Luxgen7 MPV, the EV+ receives a different front bumper and grille compartment design and clear tail lamp clusters in a lightly tinted blue color.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n | style=\"background:#CCCCCC;text-align:center\" | '''Years'''\n | style=\"background:#CCCCCC;text-align:center\" | '''Model'''\n | style=\"background:#CCCCCC;text-align:center\" | '''Power'''\n | style=\"background:#CCCCCC;text-align:center\" | '''Torque'''\n | style=\"background:#CCCCCC;text-align:center\" | '''Image'''\n |- \n  | '''2009\u2013present'''\n  | Luxgen7 MPV\n  | {{convert|175|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}\n  | {{convert|274|Nm| lbft|abbr=on}}\n  | \n |- \n | '''2010\u2013present'''\n | Luxgen7 MPV ''EV''<sup>+</sup>\n | {{convert|240|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}\n | {{convert|265|Nm|lbft|abbr=on}}\n |}\n[[File:Luxgen7 MPV EV+ 002.jpg|thumb|Luxgen7 MPV EV+]]\n\n{{clear}}\n==CEO==\nThe Luxgen 7 CEO is an executive limousine built on the MPV platform. Most parts of the vehicle body remains the same while on the exterior, the CEO receives a different grille design. It has two \"first-class\" rear seats with massage, recline and leg rest. A divider with motorized panels separates the passenger and driver compartments. The glass window can be [[frosted glass|frosted]] with the flick of a switch, along with an opaque panel that enhances privacy.\n\n[[File:Luxgen Master CEO Auto Chongqing 2012-06-07.jpg|thumb|Luxgen7 CEO]]\n\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== V7 ==\n\nThe Luxgen V7 is Luxgen's [[wheelchair accessible van]] based on the M7. It is launched in 2016 and is equipped with an extended and lower tailgate and a raised roof.\n[[File:Luxgen V7 EcoHyper.jpg|thumb|Luxgen V7 front view]]\n\n\n{{clear}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Luxgen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Luxgen7 Mpv}}\n[[Category:Luxgen vehicles|M7]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2009]]\n[[Category:Minivans]]\n[[Category:Vans]]\n[[Category:Electric vehicles]]\n[[Category:Electric vans]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2019}}{{Infobox autom